{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Unchecked Compound error codes desynchronize stablecoin accounting and can block withdrawals","locations":["Staking.sol:120","Staking.sol:127","Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:267","Staking.sol:321","Staking.sol:340","Staking.sol:356","CTokenInterface.sol:6","CTokenInterface.sol:7","CTokenInterface.sol:8"],"claim":"The stablecoin paths treat Compound interactions as if they always succeed even though `CTokenInterface.mint`, `redeemUnderlying`, and `redeem` return error codes instead of reverting. `deposit()` increments `stableCoinBalances` and user balances before `_transferToCompound()`, `withdraw()` decrements balances before `_redeemFromCompound()`, and both interest-harvest paths continue without checking the returned status, so the contract can record principal movements that never actually happened in Compound.","impact":"If a Compound market is paused, illiquid, or otherwise returns a non-zero code, the contract's internal principal accounting diverges from its real Compound position. Stablecoin deposits can be credited without being invested, withdrawals can succeed only while idle cash exists and then start reverting for later users, and interest-harvest flows operate on stale assumptions. This creates pool-wide withdrawal denial and unfair first-exit behavior for stablecoin depositors.","paths":["`deposit(stable)` -> `stableCoinBalances[token] += amount` -> user checkpoint/balance credited -> `_transferToCompound()` -> `cToken.mint(amount)` returns non-zero -> principal remains idle but the pool treats it as successfully invested","`withdraw(stable, amount)` -> internal balances reduced -> `_redeemFromCompound()` -> `redeemUnderlying(amount)` returns non-zero -> withdrawal still consumes any idle local stablecoins if available, while later users revert once local cash is exhausted"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"Emergency withdrawals leave epoch checkpoints and pool sizes unchanged","locations":["Staking.sol:61","Staking.sol:487","Staking.sol:495","Staking.sol:508","Staking.sol:558"],"claim":"`emergencyWithdraw()` zeros `balances[msg.sender][tokenAddress]` and transfers the user's non-stable tokens out, but it never updates `balanceCheckpoints`, `poolSize`, or `lastWithdrawEpochId`. As a result, epoch-based accounting continues to report the user as staked even after their principal has been removed from the contract.","impact":"A user can exit a non-stable pool yet still appear in `getEpochUserBalance()` and in initialized epoch pool totals, which corrupts the accounting intended for epoch-based reward distribution. If any rewards are computed from these checkpoint views, the user can keep receiving rewards after withdrawing, diluting or stealing rewards from users who remain staked.","paths":["Wait until `getCurrentEpoch() - lastWithdrawEpochId[token] >= 10` (already true for any pool with no recent successful withdrawals because `lastWithdrawEpochId` defaults to 0) -> call `emergencyWithdraw(token)` -> `balanceOf(user, token)` becomes 0 but `getEpochUserBalance(user, token, epoch)` still returns the old checkpointed stake","After one or more emergency withdrawals, `poolSize[token][epoch]` for initialized epochs remains overstated because the function never subtracts the removed principal"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"medium","title":"Arbitrary ERC20 deposits are credited by the requested amount instead of the actual amount received","locations":["Staking.sol:117","Staking.sol:125","Staking.sol:129","Staking.sol:136","Staking.sol:153","Staking.sol:363","Staking.sol:379","Staking.sol:398"],"claim":"For non-stable pools, the contract accepts any token address, calls raw `transferFrom`, ignores its return value, and then books `amount` directly into `balances`, user checkpoints, and epoch pool sizes. It never verifies that the transfer succeeded nor measures the real token balance delta, so fee-on-transfer, deflationary, rebasing, or false-return ERC20s can mint more stake than the contract actually received.","impact":"An attacker can stake a token that burns or withholds part of the transfer, receive full internal credit, and later withdraw the full credited amount once other users have deposited the same token. This creates phantom stake, overstated pool sizes, reward distortion, and eventual shortfalls for honest depositors in that token pool.","paths":["Deposit a transfer-tax or deflationary non-stable token -> contract receives less than `amount` but credits full `amount` in `balances` and checkpoints -> attacker later withdraws the full credited amount, pushing the deficit onto later liquidity","Deposit a token whose `transferFrom` returns `false` without moving funds -> call still succeeds because the return value is ignored -> attacker obtains stake credit without sending assets, then drains honest deposits of the same token on withdrawal"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"A single failed Compound mint can permanently brick future stablecoin deposits for that market","locations":["Staking.sol:259","Staking.sol:261","Staking.sol:262","Staking.sol:354","Staking.sol:355","Staking.sol:356","SafeERC20.sol:60"],"claim":"`_transferToCompound()` and the remint branch in `getInterest()` use `safeApprove(cToken, amount)` / `safeApprove(cToken, balance)` before calling `cToken.mint(...)`, but they never check whether `mint` returned success. If Compound returns a non-zero error before consuming the allowance, the allowance to the cToken remains non-zero, and every later call to `safeApprove` for that stablecoin reverts with `approve from non-zero to non-zero allowance`.","impact":"One paused-market or failed-mint event can permanently DOS new deposits and reinvestment for the affected stablecoin pool because the contract has no path to reset the leftover allowance back to zero. Idle principal can become stuck uninvested and all subsequent stablecoin deposits for that market revert until the contract is replaced or otherwise recovered.","paths":["`deposit(stable)` -> `safeApprove(cToken, amount)` succeeds -> `cToken.mint(amount)` returns non-zero and does not pull funds -> allowance stays non-zero -> every later stablecoin deposit for that market reverts inside `safeApprove`","`getInterest(token)` -> redeem succeeds or partially succeeds -> `safeApprove(cToken, balance)` succeeds -> remint `mint(balance)` returns non-zero -> leftover allowance blocks all future remints and deposits for that stablecoin"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex"]}],"rejected_candidates":[]}
